VALORANT: An Up & Coming Competitive Tac-Shooter

An analysis of ACS (Average Combat Score) at official Riot events in relation to the agents that are being played.

By Gurjit Dhaliwal

CMSC320 December 11th, 2022

Introduction

VALORANT is a tactical shooter created by Riot Games in 2020 that has taken off in the field of E-Sports. Tactical Shooters are games that aim to simulate combat through slow-paced, team-oriented gameplay. Each bullet is devastating, resulting in a focus on strategy and precise aim. VALORANT however, changes the scene of competitive tac-shooters by bringing characters and abilties into the field. It's been categorized as a crossover between Overwatch and CS:GO. Originally, games such as Counter Strike: Global Offensive (CS:GO) had a bland character model who would purchase flashbangs, smokes, and molotovs. VALORANT has created characters that have their own unique kits, leaving some characters as designated "smoking" or "flashing" agents and placing characters into roles.

this photo shows a piece of gameplay: we see an agent firing a weapon at an enemy alongside Viper & her wall (smoke ability).

There are 5 maps currently in rotation with 20 different agents for players. In VALORANT, there are currently four classes that agents are categorized as:

CONTROLLER -> Characters who posses smokes & can block off lines of sight.

Current Controllers: Brimstone, Astra, Omen, Viper.

SENTINEL -> Defense-oriented characters who watch for flanks and lockdown bomb sites.

Current Sentinels: Killjoy, Cypher, Sage.

DUELIST -> Self-sufficent fragging characters, everything in their kit enables them to do damage and make space.

Current Duelists: Jett, Phoenix, Reyna, Raze, Yoru.

INITIATOR -> Intelligence-oriented characters who can set up their allies for success through their abilities (i.e. a drone/flash).

Current Initiators: KAY/O, Breach, Skye, Sova.

These classes define what kits an agent has, making them adept at doing what their class is designed to do. An example, Phoenix is a duelist. His abilities are: two fast flashbangs, a recharging molotov, a wall of flame to block lines of sight, and an ultimate ability which gives Phoenix a second life. It makes sense that he is a duelist as all of his skills accenuate his ability to seek engagements and make space.

The fundamentals of the game remains the same as CS:GO. One team starts as the "attackers". In each round, they must either plant the bomb and ensure it detonates or eliminate the opposing team. The other team are our "defenders". They must defend the map and prevent the bomb from being planted or eliminate all of the attackers. Each round lasts for 2 minutes with teams switching sides after playing 12 rounds. The first team to win 13 rounds will win the game, unless overtime is triggered. Overtime is won by a team winning 2 rounds in a row after a 12 - 12 scoreline has been reached.

For more information on VALORANT: https://playvalorant.com/en-sg/

Even though VALORANT is a relatively young game, it recently won the title for Best eSports Game of the Year. Riot has held multiple tournaments and events throughout the last 2 years. These events have been international, involving teams from most major regions such as APAC, EU, BRAZIL, LATAM, CHINA, and others. There have been events officially hosted by Riot as well as other 3rd party tournaments. However, Riot doesn't like to release it's datasets from these tournaments. But someone on Kaggle did all of the hard work for me! For this project, I found a dataset that has data for EVERY professional VALORANT match up until January 2022. This includes every single match played until the first official VALORANT: Champions - the World Championship for VALORANT.

Link to the dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/visualize25/valorant-pro-matches-full-data

For this tutorial, my goal is to tidy the plethora of data given to us, provide insight into which agents have the highest average combat score (ACS) vs Win Percentage, and predict win percentage based on agent and their ACS. Each character is different in VALORANT, we wouldn't expect a sentinel to match a duelist's ACS. There's also a trend that mechanically gifted players opt to play duelist (roles where they can utilize their precise aim) over other roles. We see examples of this with SEN TenZ, 100T Asuna, and many of the other gifted "aim" players in the scene. These are the guys who should be accumulating multiple kills each round based on raw skill - surely, they would play a role that compliments their aim.

A note into ACS: ACS effectively captures a player's impact on a match. Points are awarded for getting kills & doing damage, but kills early in a round will give you more points than kills at the end. ACS also accounts for multi-kills, using proper utility, and clutching (winning a round when the odds are against you).

If you are not familiar with VALORANT, I would recommend trying it out! It's fun for a while but like any Riot game, the competitive mode destroys your sanity. This walkthrough should show the capabilties of each class of agent in terms of ACS, potentially giving inspiration for which agent to play.

For people who know about VALORANT, this tutorial aims to show how the professionals are utilizing agents. We will attempt to see the true potential that these agents have. Plus, it's cool to learn something new!

Example questions that will hopefully be answered:

Does it tend to be duelists with the highest ACS or can other roles achieve this? What does the win percentage per agent look like?

Let's meet the data!

There's a couple modules we'll be using extensively throughout this project: pandas , numpy, and sqlite3.

We will also utilize scikit-learn, seaborn, and of course Python3!

This data is stored in an sqlite file from Kaggle - so we're going to have to use SQLite3 to connect and pull out the tables.

There are 4 tables within our SQL file:

1) Matches -> Table shows EVERY match for professional Valorant. Shows teams, tournament name, series score, and much more.

2) Games -> Table shows maps played and individual scores per map. These can be linked to Matches through MatchID.

3) Game_Scoreboard -> Table shows the overall scoreboard of each map. Also shows first bloods, multi-kills, deaths per player per map, and more detailed stats. Can be linked to Game via GameID.

4) There is 4th table in the dataset -> GameRounds. This table shows the breakdown PER round of: economy, who won each round, win and buy type. However, I will be ignoring this for this project.

Tidying the Data

Like I said before, there have been dozens of tournaments that've occured for VALORANT. "Nerd Street" is a 3rd party organization which used to run Winter Championship tournaments. These were popular at the start prior to Riot operating their own events. But once Riot started running official competitions, the largest organizations and best players shifted to play in those. We saw the rise of VALORANT teamsa across the globe as they represented their country and played other nations, leading up to an international VALORANT: Champions Tour. For the purposes of this project, I will be ignoring all data from non-Riot events.

With this modification, riotframe only contains match data from official Riot events. A match is defined as a series of maps, commonly best of 3. There are occasionally best of 5 matches but these are always in the Grand Finals. In this dataset, we have the following columns:

  • MatchID - Unique ID per match. Lets us lookup matches in other tables.
  • Date
  • Patch

There's one more data modification we need to do in order to properly utilize the ACS data. We need another value to plot on the other axis, something to demonstrate how much ACS matters. We're going need to create a win % column for every player.

To do this, we will be modifying the riotscores_trim table and adding the amount of games they've won/lost to the table. Our approach for doing this will be:

1) Take an entire row from riotscores_trim. Each row holds a player's name and a specific GameID. 2) Search riotgames_trim with the GameID as riotgames_trim holds values for who won the game. 3) Compare the full team name who won the game to our player's team abbreviation. 4) If every character in the team abbreviation matches that in the winner's name, our player won. Add a value of PlayerName+"_win" to a list named count_list. Otherwise, add a value of PlayerName+"_loss" to the list. 5) After parsing every single player, we'll create a new Series called l. This Series will hold the frequency of wins/losses for each player. 6) Finally, we'll add columns for win & loss by utilizing the values from this Series l.

In [382]:
#this code is so god damn intense LOL
#teamabbr will hold the current row (1 player's team abbreviation
#tbl holds a DF that contains the match corresponding to the current player's game we're examining
#basically, this function takes an an entry from riotscores and checks if that player won the game they played or not
def count_winloss(teamabbr,tbl):
    #convert both to lowercase to eliminate caps
    teamabbr = teamabbr.lower()
    full = tbl["Winner"].values[0].lower()
    #break the abbreviation into a list so we can examine if each char is in the full name
    listy = list(teamabbr)
    
    #the way this'll work is for each char in abbr, if it's in the fullname we append T otherwise F
    bool_list = []
    for char in listy:
        if char in full:
            bool_list.append(True)
        else:
            bool_list.append(False)
    #if every char didn't match from abbr in fullname, it's not the right team so return false.
    #i.e they didn't win
    if False in bool_list:
        return False
    
    else:
    #otherwise, they won as each char matched in the full name
        return True

#our list that will hold the values before we make the series
count_list = []
riotscores_trim.apply(lambda row: count_list.append(row.PlayerName + "_win") if count_winloss(row.TeamAbbreviation,riotgames_trim[riotgames_trim['GameID'] == row.GameID]) else count_list.append(row.PlayerName + "_loss"), axis=1)

We can see that l holds a count of how many wins/losses each player has. Now, we'll create two helper methods to allow us to fill in the Wins & Lost columns of our table.

1) get_wins(player) -> Takes in a player's name, appends "_win" to their string and returns the number of wins. 2) get_loss(player) -> Takes in a player's name, appends "_win" to their string and returns the number of losses.

After filling these columns, we'll create another column for GamesPlayed and WinPercentage (Win_Perc).

In [384]:
def get_wins(player):
    #look up the player in l
    y = l[l['player_stat'] == player+'_win']
    #if there's no entry, then the player has no wins. return 0
    if y.values.size == 0:
        return(0)
    else:
        #otherwise, return the # of wins
        return(y.values[0][1:2][0])
    
def get_loss(player):
    y = l[l['player_stat'] == player+'_loss']
    #if there's no entry, the player has no losses. return 0
    if y.values.size == 0:
        return(0)
    else:
        #otherwise return # of losses
        return(y.values[0][1:2][0])

riotscores_trim['Wins'] = riotscores_trim['PlayerName'].apply(lambda x: get_wins(x))
riotscores_trim['Lost'] = riotscores_trim['PlayerName'].apply(lambda x: get_loss(x))
In [385]:
riotscores_trim['GamesPlayed'] = riotscores_trim['Wins'] + riotscores_trim['Lost']
riotscores_trim['Win_Perc'] = riotscores_trim['Wins'] / riotscores_trim['GamesPlayed']

Our original scatterplot didn't tell us much as there was just way too much data being shown at once. We could somewhat see the frequency of agents, but let's create another plot to get a better visualization.

We'll condense this plot and create a plot that shows average ACS vs average win percentage per agent. This way we can see the average stats per character in the game. However, we have some outliers on both ends. Sometimes players play absolute scrubs, so their ACS is artifically high. An example would be berLIN's 637 ACS game. We also have the other end, those scrubs who get crushed, leaving their ACS artifically low. An example is ABC who got absolutely crushed by berLIN.

The same problem is present in the win percentages. Some players have a 100% win rate as they won every game they played. They may have been subbed out or dropped after a tournament/game. There are other players who play for fun and constantly lose, leaving them with a win percentage of 0%.

To avoid the impact of these outliers, we'll utilize the median ACS/Win Percentage as our average.

Now let's make our dataframe for the averages & create the graph.

In [391]:
agent_groups = riotscores_trim.groupby(['Agent'])
agents = []
avg_acs = []
avg_winperc = []

for agent, agent_tbl in agent_groups:
    agents.append(agent)
    avg_acs.append(agent_tbl['ACS'].median())

Linear Regression on Each Agent's Scatter Plot

Let's take a closer look at the relationship between ACS and Win Percentage per Agent. We'll create scatterplots with a regression line for each agent. This'll allow us to see if there's any correlation between ACS and win_percentage.

We'll import stats here so we can obtain the co-efficients of each linear fit. I'll append the first 5 digits of the slope to the title for easy viewing. There will also be a table with each agent's slope, intercept, and p_value.

In [395]:
from scipy import stats

for agent, agent_tbl in agent_groups:
    slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(agent_tbl['ACS'],agent_tbl['Win_Perc'])
    sns.lmplot(x="ACS", y="Win_Perc",data=agent_tbl).fig.suptitle("ACS vs Win Percentage for {} : Slope={:.5f}".format(agent[0].upper()+agent[1:],slope),fontsize=12)

Let's analyze the plots above. Our agents with the highest slope are Phoenix, Omen, Yoru, Jett, Reyna. These agents' regression lines are much steeper than others, implying the higher ACS, the more likely you are to win on these agents. These character have heavy game impact - if you do exceptional with them, your odds of winning increase a good amount.

Despite these slopes, the p-values for most of our agents is incredibly low. This may mean that there isn't a heavy correlation between ACS and Win Percentage for a majority of them. KAY/O and Yoru are the only two characters that have a p-value without a negative exponent. This is still less than a p-value of 0.05 which normally implies a trend.

Hypothesis Testing/ML

In this final section of the tutorial, we'll attempt to develop a model that can accurately predict win percentage of a game based on ACS. We will be utilizing a linear regression model. We will split our data into a training set and a testing set to properly train it. We will also One-Hot Encode our agents so that our model will be able to process them.

One-Hot Encoding takes categorical variables such as agent names, and transforms them into numericals or something that can be processed by an algorithm.

# Source referenced: https://jiglesia3.github.io/
#utilized their R6S one-hot encoder - it's great
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn import preprocessing

def dummyEncode(df):
    # Filters through dataframe and recognizes categorical variables
    columnsToEncode = list(df.select_dtypes(include=['category','object']))
    le = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
    for feature in columnsToEncode:
        try:
            df[feature] = le.fit_transform(df[feature])
        except:
            print('Error encoding '+feature)
    return df

Values of 1 or 0 for Win_Perc within our dataframe have potential to skew our results from the machine learning algorithm. We'll filter these values out within our new encoded_df.
